"(1)  \nA shimmering haze hung over the spring morning, pressing the cobblestones of Washington Square into the warmth of a city still waking. Distant music hummed—a lullaby, perhaps—a melody threading through the gentle clink and scrape of chisels from a block of crystal white far across the park. The world felt suspended, as if the air itself were waiting to crystallize, every breath leaving a faint trace of frost.\n\n(2)  \nAlong the curving iron railings, clusters of onlookers gathered like bees drawn to a hive. Tents of pale blue and glass reflected the morning sun, their contents: sculptures rising tall as spires, each more magnificent than the last. The sculptures twisted in forms impossible in stone—swans with feathers made of prismatic shards, wolves that seemed to breathe mist, and a towering figure of a violinist whose body melted upward like snow.\n\n(3)  \nHenry watched from a shadowed nook under a willow, hands deep in the pockets of his navy coat. He’d left the house with no plan, drawn by the promise of cold and transformation. The city’s pulse was subdued today, softened by the season’s first touch and the quiet spectacle before him—an alchemy of art and ephemeral beauty.\n\n(4)  \nHe could smell the faintest bite of winter—icy ammonia from the sculptures’ creation, mingled with the earthy tang of wet grass beneath the feet of passersby. Vendors moved quietly along their paths, their arms laden with blocks of blue ice still quivering. Children stopped, wide-eyed, as a sculptor deftly carved a fox from a single chunk, the ice flaking like snow with every pass of the blade.\n\n(5)  \nHenry’s gaze lingered on a monumental sculpture in the center of the gathering: two lovers, mid-embrace, bodies formed not from marble but from frozen water, skin translucent in the daylight. Light refracted through it in kaleidoscopic patterns, casting rainbows that danced around the heads of nearby spectators. For a moment, it was as if the sculpture was alive with hidden currents.\n\n(6)  \nA soft chime sounded nearby, and a woman emerged from behind a canvas awning, her eyes bright as the sculptures around her. She handed out pamphlets, her fingers cool from the ice blocks she handled. Henry found his feet moving almost of their own accord, curiosity piqued by the vibrant energy she exuded as she described"